<subSubSection id="B5F9654B8907867BFD1DFCD6FDCFFA83" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="description">
<paragraph id="FD5C36C08907867BFD1DFCD6FDA9FEA6" blockId="10.[691,1219,856,967]" lastBlockId="11.[123,652,193,1301]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
This species was common between 800 and 
<quantity id="3A1B9B258907867AFD2BFCFBFCF9FC1A" box="[742,832,885,908]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" unit="m" value="1700.0">1700 m</quantity>
on Mt. Muong Cha and Mt. Tay Con Linh II. It was found associated with fast­moving water: among cascades, in splash zones, on mossy boulders midstream, along wet, rocky walls, and in streamside forest to 
<specimenCount id="EBE5FD498906867BFF3EFF72FE96FE85" box="[243,303,252,275]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="generic">
<quantity id="3A1B9B258906867BFF3EFF72FE92FE85" box="[243,299,252,275]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="m" value="3.0">3 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
Males had distended vocal pouches and females were gravid.
</paragraph>
